{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520528"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:25:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:25:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13210"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13210"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.5,0.07,0.02,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5646"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51967"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5646"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13210"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37270"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9662"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9694"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14695"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15038"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45996"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51967"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 46-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health check for insurance purposes. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Laboratory investigations show slightly elevated liver enzymes. An upper abdominal ultrasound reveals a normal appearing gallbladder, apart from a 12 mm polyp within the body of the gallbladder. There are no gallstones and the rest of the biliary tree appears normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance alone","Repeat ultrasound in six months","Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography","Endoscopic ultrasound","Laparoscopic cholecystectomy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has been found to have a gallbladder polyp measuring 12 mm. Gallbladder polyps are common incidental findings, with the majority being small (\u0026lt;1 cm), benign, and often multiple. However, there is a small risk of malignancy, which correlates with the size of the polyp.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic cholecystectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for this patient. Gallbladder polyps measuring \u22651 cm have a moderate risk of malignancy. In patients with polyps \u22651 cm, laparoscopic cholecystectomy is recommended to eliminate the risk of gallbladder carcinoma, provided the patient is fit for and accepts surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance alone\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for polyps \u0026lt;5 mm without risk factors for malignancy. However, for a 12 mm polyp, this approach would be inadequate given the increased risk of malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat ultrasound in six months\u003C/strong\u003E is the recommended approach for gallbladder polyps of size 6-9 mm. For polyps \u22651 cm, as in this case, immediate intervention rather than surveillance is warranted due to the higher risk of malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography\u003C/strong\u003E (ERCP) is an established treatment for choledocholithiasis but plays no role in the management of gallbladder polyps. It would be an inappropriate and unnecessarily invasive procedure in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopic ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E (EUS) may provide additional information in the diagnosis of gallbladder polyps and can be considered in difficult cases to aid decision-making. However, it is not routinely recommended and is unnecessary in this case where the diagnosis is clear from the abdominal ultrasound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the management of gallbladder polyps depends primarily on their size. Polyps \u0026lt;5 mm can often be discharged with reassurance, those 6-9 mm require surveillance, and those \u22651 cm, as in this case, should be managed with laparoscopic cholecystectomy due to the moderate risk of malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Gallbladder polyps carry a small risk of malignant change.","Gallbladder polyps measuring \u22651 cm have a moderate risk of malignancy, and laparoscopic cholecystectomy should be offered."],"references":["Foley KG, Lahaye MJ, Thoeni RF, Soltes M, Dewhurst C, Barbu ST, et al. Management and follow-up of gallbladder polyps: updated joint guidelines between the ESGAR, EAES, EFISDS and ESGE. Eur Radiol [Internet]. 2022 May 1 [cited 2023 Aug 3];32(5):3358\u201368. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9038818/ doi: 10.1007/s00330-021-08384-w"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37270"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13210"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37270"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-30T16:17:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-30T21:10:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5646"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51967"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","